{"title_page": "Narvik Shield", "text_new": "{{Infobox military award\n|name=Narvik Shield<br>''Narvikschild''\n|image=Narvikschild (ohne Tuch).png\n|image_size=150px\n|caption=Narvik Shield in silver\n|awarded_by=[[Nazi Germany]]\n|type=[[Badge]]\n|eligibility=Military personnel\n|for=Taking part in the [[Battles of Narvik]]\n|campaign=[[World War II]]\n|status=Obsolete\n|description=\n|clasps=\n|established=19 August 1940\n|first_award=[[Eduard Dietl]] 21 March 1941\n|last_award=15 June 1943\n|total=8,577{{sfn|Angolia|1987|p=276}}\n|posthumous=680{{sfn|Williamson|2012|p=18}}                \n|recipients=\n|individual=\n|higher=\n|same=\n|lower=\n|related=\n|image2=Narvik_Gold.jpg\n|image_size2=110px\n|caption2=1957 version in gold\n}}\nThe '''Narvik Shield''' ({{Lang-de|Narvikschild}}) was a [[World War II]] [[Nazi Germany|German]] military decoration awarded to all German forces that took part in the [[battles of Narvik]] between 9 April and 8 June 1940. It was instituted on 19 August 1940 by [[Adolf Hitler]]. The ''Oberkommando der Wehrmacht'' (OKW) published the order the same day. It was bestowed by General [[Eduard Dietl]], the commander of Army Group Narvik.{{sfn|Angolia|1987|p=276}}{{sfn|Ailsby|1987|p=96}}\n\nThe award was the first of a series of [[Campaign shields (Wehrmacht)|arm shield campaign awards]].{{sfn|Littlejohn|1968|p=142}} A total of 8,577 personnel received the award.{{sfn|Angolia|1987|p=276}} Specifically: 2,755 to the [[German Army (Wehrmacht)|army]], 2,161 to the ''[[Kriegsmarine]]'', and 3,661 to the [[Luftwaffe]].{{sfn| Williamson|2012|p=18}} \n\n==Design==\nDesigned by Professor Dr. [[Richard Klein (artist)|Richard Klein]] of Munich, the shield is narrow with a pointed base and, at its apex, has an eagle with down-swept wings clutching a laurel wreath that surrounds a swastika. Below this in capital letters is written <tt>NARVIK</tt>. The body of the shield features an [[edelweiss]] (representing the [[Gebirgsj\u00e4ger|army mountain troops]]), an anchor (representing the ''Kriegsmarine''), and propeller (for the Luftwaffe). The anchor and propeller are crossed, with the edelweiss placed at the top of the X. The numbers <tt>19</tt> and <tt>40</tt> appear at the top corners of the main body of the shield.{{sfn|Angolia|1987|pp=277}}{{sfn|Ailsby|1987|p=96}}\n\nThe shield was hollow backed and stamped from sheet metal which was usually zinc. The shield was awarded in two versions: silver-gray versions for army and Luftwaffe and a gilded (golden coloured) version for ''Kriegsmarine''.{{sfn|Angolia|1987|pp=277}} It was mounted on a cloth backing corresponding to the colour of the uniform, and worn on the upper left arm of the uniform.{{sfn|Littlejohn|1968|p=142}} \n\n===1957 version===\nIn 1957, the Narvik Shield, along with many other German military decorations of World War II, was reauthorized for wear by qualifying veterans.<ref>{{cite web|title=Bundesgesetzblatt Teil III, Gliederungsnummer 1132-1\".|url=http://bundesrecht.juris.de/ordeng/BJNR008440957.html|publisher=|accessdate=2019-10-23}}</ref> The new version was of same design, but without the eagle and [[swastika]] symbol of Nazi Germany.\n\n==See also==\n* [[Campaign shields (Wehrmacht)]]\n* [[Cholm Shield]]\n* [[Crimea Shield]]\n* [[Demyansk Shield]]\n* [[Kuban Shield]]\n* [[Lappland Shield]]\n* [[Warsaw Shield]]\n\n== Notes ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== References ==\n*{{cite book | last = Ailsby | first = Christopher | title = Combat Medals of the Third Reich | publisher = HarperCollins | year = 1987 | isbn = 978-0850598223 | ref = harv }}\n*{{cite book | last = Angolia | first = John | title = For F\u00fchrer and Fatherland: Military Awards of the Third Reich | publisher = R. James Bender Publishing | year = 1987 | isbn = 0912138149 | ref = harv }}\n*{{cite book | last = Littlejohn | first =David and Dodkins, Colonel C. M. | title = Orders, Decorations, Medals and Badges of the Third Reich | publisher = R. James Bender Publishing, California | year = 1968 | isbn = 978-0854200801}}\n*{{cite book | last =  Williamson | first = Gordon | title = World War II German Battle Insignia | publisher = Bloomsbury Publishing | year = 2012 | isbn = 1841763527 | ref = harv }}\n*German Federal law: [http://bundesrecht.juris.de/ordeng/BJNR008440957.html Bundesministerium der Justiz: Gesetz \u00fcber Titel, Orden und Ehrenzeichen, 26.7.1957. Bundesgesetzblatt Teil III, Gliederungsnummer 1132-1]\n\n\n{{List of military decorations of the Third Reich |state=collapsed}}\n{{Subject bar\n| portal1=Military of Germany\n| portal2=World War II\n}}\n\n[[Category:Military awards and decorations of Nazi Germany]]\n[[Category:Awards established in 1940]]\n[[Category:1940 establishments in Germany]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox military award\n|name=Narvik Shield<br>''Narvikschild''\n|image=Narvikschild farbe silber.jpg\n|image_size=150px\n|caption=Narvik Shield in silver\n|awarded_by=[[Nazi Germany]]\n|type=[[Badge]]\n|eligibility=Military personnel\n|for=Taking part in the [[Battles of Narvik]]\n|campaign=[[World War II]]\n|status=Obsolete\n|description=\n|clasps=\n|established=19 August 1940\n|first_award=[[Eduard Dietl]] 21 March 1941\n|last_award=15 June 1943\n|total=8,577{{sfn|Angolia|1987|p=276}}\n|posthumous=680{{sfn|Williamson|2012|p=18}}                \n|recipients=\n|individual=\n|higher=\n|same=\n|lower=\n|related=\n|image2=Narvik_Gold.jpg\n|image_size2=110px\n|caption2=1957 version in gold\n}}\nThe '''Narvik Shield''' ({{Lang-de|Narvikschild}}) was a [[World War II]] [[Nazi Germany|German]] military decoration awarded to all German forces that took part in the [[battles of Narvik]] between 9 April and 8 June 1940. It was instituted on 19 August 1940 by [[Adolf Hitler]]. The ''Oberkommando der Wehrmacht'' (OKW) published the order the same day. It was bestowed by General [[Eduard Dietl]], the commander of Army Group Narvik.{{sfn|Angolia|1987|p=276}}{{sfn|Ailsby|1987|p=96}}\n\nThe award was the first of a series of [[Campaign shields (Wehrmacht)|arm shield campaign awards]].{{sfn|Littlejohn|1968|p=142}} A total of 8,577 personnel received the award.{{sfn|Angolia|1987|p=276}} Specifically: 2,755 to the [[German Army (Wehrmacht)|army]], 2,161 to the ''[[Kriegsmarine]]'', and 3,661 to the [[Luftwaffe]].{{sfn| Williamson|2012|p=18}} \n\n==Design==\nDesigned by Professor Dr. [[Richard Klein (artist)|Richard Klein]] of Munich, the shield is narrow with a pointed base and, at its apex, has an eagle with down-swept wings clutching a laurel wreath that surrounds a swastika. Below this in capital letters is written <tt>NARVIK</tt>. The body of the shield features an [[edelweiss]] (representing the [[Gebirgsj\u00e4ger|army mountain troops]]), an anchor (representing the ''Kriegsmarine''), and propeller (for the Luftwaffe). The anchor and propeller are crossed, with the edelweiss placed at the top of the X. The numbers <tt>19</tt> and <tt>40</tt> appear at the top corners of the main body of the shield.{{sfn|Angolia|1987|pp=277}}{{sfn|Ailsby|1987|p=96}}\n\nThe shield was hollow backed and stamped from sheet metal which was usually zinc. The shield was awarded in two versions: silver-gray versions for army and Luftwaffe and a gilded (golden coloured) version for ''Kriegsmarine''.{{sfn|Angolia|1987|pp=277}} It was mounted on a cloth backing corresponding to the colour of the uniform, and worn on the upper left arm of the uniform.{{sfn|Littlejohn|1968|p=142}} \n\n===1957 version===\nIn 1957, the Narvik Shield, along with many other German military decorations of World War II, was reauthorized for wear by qualifying veterans.<ref>{{cite web|title=Bundesgesetzblatt Teil III, Gliederungsnummer 1132-1\".|url=http://bundesrecht.juris.de/ordeng/BJNR008440957.html|publisher=|accessdate=2019-10-23}}</ref> The new version was of same design, but without the eagle and [[swastika]] symbol of Nazi Germany.\n\n==See also==\n* [[Campaign shields (Wehrmacht)]]\n* [[Cholm Shield]]\n* [[Crimea Shield]]\n* [[Demyansk Shield]]\n* [[Kuban Shield]]\n* [[Lappland Shield]]\n* [[Warsaw Shield]]\n\n== Notes ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== References ==\n*{{cite book | last = Ailsby | first = Christopher | title = Combat Medals of the Third Reich | publisher = HarperCollins | year = 1987 | isbn = 978-0850598223 | ref = harv }}\n*{{cite book | last = Angolia | first = John | title = For F\u00fchrer and Fatherland: Military Awards of the Third Reich | publisher = R. James Bender Publishing | year = 1987 | isbn = 0912138149 | ref = harv }}\n*{{cite book | last = Littlejohn | first =David and Dodkins, Colonel C. M. | title = Orders, Decorations, Medals and Badges of the Third Reich | publisher = R. James Bender Publishing, California | year = 1968 | isbn = 978-0854200801}}\n*{{cite book | last =  Williamson | first = Gordon | title = World War II German Battle Insignia | publisher = Bloomsbury Publishing | year = 2012 | isbn = 1841763527 | ref = harv }}\n*German Federal law: [http://bundesrecht.juris.de/ordeng/BJNR008440957.html Bundesministerium der Justiz: Gesetz \u00fcber Titel, Orden und Ehrenzeichen, 26.7.1957. Bundesgesetzblatt Teil III, Gliederungsnummer 1132-1]\n\n\n{{List of military decorations of the Third Reich |state=collapsed}}\n{{Subject bar\n| portal1=Military of Germany\n| portal2=World War II\n}}\n\n[[Category:Military awards and decorations of Nazi Germany]]\n[[Category:Awards established in 1940]]\n[[Category:1940 establishments in Germany]]\n", "name_user": "Gunnar.offel", "label": "safe", "comment": "PNG", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Narvik_Shield"}
